# TURINGOS AGENT PROTOCOL — FOLLOW THIS EVERY SESSION, NO EXCEPTIONS

You are a coding agent working on **TuringOS**: a CP/M-era 8-bit operating system modeled strictly as a Turing Machine, written in C99, targeting an Intel 8080 emulator. Before you write a single line of code or make any change, you must execute the following read-first protocol.

---

## STEP 1 — READ `spec.md`

Open and read `spec.md` fully before starting any task.

`spec.md` contains:
- The complete Turing Machine model mapping (tape / head / states / transition function)
- The 8080 architecture constraints
- Every component's interface, responsibility, and file location
- The directory structure
- Build and Docker setup
- What you are NOT allowed to do

If your planned change contradicts anything in `spec.md`, **stop and reconcile the spec first** before writing code.

---

## STEP 2 — READ `progress.md`

Open and read `progress.md` fully before starting any task.

`progress.md` contains:
- Every task broken down by component
- Status markers: `[ ]` = not started, `[~]` = in progress, `[x]` = complete
- Blockers and dependencies between tasks
- The canonical "what to work on next"

Pick only tasks that are `[ ]` and have their dependencies marked `[x]`. Do not work on tasks that are `[~]` unless you are the agent who set them in progress. Do not skip ahead.

---

## STEP 3 — READ `remember.md`

Open and read `remember.md` fully before starting any task.

`remember.md` contains:
- Bugs that were found and fixed (so you don't re-introduce them)
- Architectural decisions made mid-build (with rationale)
- Known gotchas, tricky edge cases, and tested assumptions
- Any deviations from `spec.md` that were approved and why

This file is **append-only**. Never delete or overwrite entries. Never reformat existing entries.

---

## STEP 4 — DO YOUR WORK

Now you may write code. Stay within your assigned component. Do not refactor other components unless `spec.md` explicitly says they share an interface with yours.

After any code change, you must run the test suite before considering the task done:
- Run `make test`
- If tests fail, fix the issue and re-run `make test` until all tests pass
- Do not mark work complete in `progress.md` or `remember.md` until tests pass

**Timeouts when adding or changing tests:** Unless you are absolutely sure a timeout is unnecessary (for example, a pure compile-time unit test that cannot loop), give every path that could hang a bounded wait: shell scripts should wrap subprocesses with `timeout` / `gtimeout` or equivalent; C harnesses that drive the emulator with a step loop must cap total steps or wall time; integration tests that spawn `turingos` or the compiler must not run unbounded. Prefer explicit thresholds and clear failure messages over infinite waits.

---

## STEP 5 — UPDATE `progress.md` WHEN DONE

After completing work:
- Change `[~]` to `[x]` for finished tasks
- Add any new sub-tasks you discovered under the relevant component
- Note any blockers you hit under the task with a `> BLOCKER:` line

---

## STEP 6 — UPDATE `remember.md` WHEN DONE

After completing work, append a new dated entry for:
- Any bug you fixed (describe root cause + fix)
- Any decision you made that isn't obvious from the code
- Any assumption you tested or validated
- Any deviation from `spec.md` (must include justification)

Format:
```
## [YYYY-MM-DD] <component> — <short title>
<body: what happened, why, what was done>
```

---

## HARD CONSTRAINTS — NEVER VIOLATE THESE

These are the Turing Machine architectural laws. They are not preferences or guidelines.

- **Tape** = 64KB flat memory array (`uint8_t mem[65536]`). No malloc on the tape. No virtual memory. No paging. No segmentation beyond the TM state machine's own bookkeeping.
- **Head** = 8080 Program Counter (`uint16_t pc`). The head moves by executing 8080 instructions.
- **Alphabet** = bytes (0x00–0xFF). Every cell on the tape is one byte.
- **States** = the OS kernel FSM: `BOOT → IDLE → SHELL → RUNNING → SYSCALL → HALT`. The kernel's `state` variable is the TM state register.
- **Transition function** = the fetch-decode-execute loop + the BIOS/syscall dispatcher. This is the only place state transitions are legal.
- **Addresses are `uint16_t`** everywhere. No 32-bit addresses. No pointers into host memory passed into the emulator.
- **All kernel and emulator code is C99** — no C++, no C11 VLAs, no GCC extensions unless unavoidable and documented in `remember.md`.
- **Visualization is Python 3 + pygame only** — no other frameworks, no web servers, no Electron.
- **No new external C dependencies** without updating `spec.md` and getting a comment added to `remember.md`.

